    {
      "id": "readonly-queue-review",
      "title": "Read-only review identifies two behavioral defects",
      "category": "review",
      "passed": true,
      "score": 10,
      "maxScore": 10,
      "latencyMs": 12541,
      "terminal": "completed",
      "reply": "Two concrete behavioral defects:\n\n**1. `drain` processes one extra job per call (off-by-one)**\n```js\nfor (let index = 0; index <= Math.min(limit, queue.length); index++)\n```\nThe `<=` causes the loop to run `Math.min(limit, queue.length) + 1` times. For example, `limit = 3` and `queue.length = 5` iterates indices `0,1,2,3` — four items, not three. This violates the rate limit and can over-consume the queue.\n\n**2. `acknowledge` returns success before the store confirms removal**\n```js\nexport async function acknowledge(store, id) {\n  store.remove(id)\n  return { acknowledged: true }\n}\n```\n`store.remove(id)` is not `await`ed. If `store.remove` returns a promise (typical for persistent stores), the function resolves `{ acknowledged: true }` before the removal finishes or fails. If the store rejects or crashes, the caller thinks the job is acknowledged, but the item remains in the store — leading to duplicate processing or a lost/inconsistent acknowledgment.",
